<% page_title "Developer and Designer Resumes Made Better" %>

<% content_for :head do %>
    <hgroup>
        <h1>
            Re&#45;CV.com
        </h1>
        <h2>Make your resume make sense.</h2>
    </hgroup>
    <a href="/signup" class="action-button" title="">Create a resume!</a>&nbsp;
    <% if current_user %>
        <a href="/logout" title="">Log out</a>
    <% else %>
        <a href="/login" title="">Log in</a>
    <% end %>
<% end %>

<% content_for :main do %>
    <section class="primary extended">
        <h1>
            Goodbye alphabet soup; hello clarity!
        </h1>
        <h2>This doesn&rsquo;t say much:</h2>
        <blockquote>
            HTML5, CSS, PHP, RoR, JS, jQuery, JSON, XML, XSLT, XSL-FO, C++,
            AJAX, REST, XHTML, RSS, MVC, MVVM, JSP, SVN, HAML, LESS,
            SASS/SCSS, TCP/IP, IA, UX, UI, IxD, i18n, a11y, RDF,
            SVG, WebGL, XPath, ARIA, WOFF
        </blockquote>
        <h2>But a Re&#45;CV resume speaks volumes.</h2>
        <a href="<%= resume_path(@demo.user_id, @demo.resume_id) %>" class="action-button huge">View the demo resume</a>
    </section>
    <section class="secondary extended">
        <h1>Link your skills to jobs</h1>
        <p>
            Say an employer wants to know if you have experience with <em>Ruby on Rails</em>, but
            you&rsquo;ve used <em>Django</em> at your last two jobs. On a traditional resume, the employer
            might have to go to page 2. <strong>With Re&#45;CV, he can just click &ldquo;Ruby on Rails&rdquo;.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>He&rsquo;ll see when you last used Rails, where you used it, and what you did with it. In one click!</p>
    </section>

    <section class="secondary extended">
        <h1>Paint a picture of a year in your career</h1>
        <img />
        <p>
            Say an employer wants to know what you&rsquo;ve been up to recently.
            <strong>With Re&#45;CV, he can just click on 2013.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            He&rsquo;ll see where you&rsquo;ve worked and what you&rsquo;ve worked on (including side projects),
            what skills and software you&rsquo;ve used, and any highlights you list.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="secondary extended">
        <h1>Show what you did with your skills</h1>
        <img />
        <p>
            <strong>Highlights</strong> let you provide examples of the best work you&rsquo;ve done.
            So when you say you know <em>CSS3</em>, you can back it up!
        </p>
    </section>
<% end %>